What will he do? ČSSD in Prague doesn’t know Voldemort or the confectioner’s shop
The new city councilors from the ČSSD will probably have to overcome a certain language barrier in order to understand their old-new colleagues from the ODS in the Prague council and council.
The daily Aktuálně.cz "tried" the members of the new council from the ČSSD, as they know the notoriously established slang, which was created at the town hall during the last years when Prague was ruled by the current coalition partners.
The coded dictionary, introduced by the Prague political elite during the previous era of the Mayor Pavel Bém, describes some of the most famous figures, situations and cases in the metropolis.
Surprisingly, it turned out that the new councillors did not understand well-known terms.
At least that's what he says.
"Who's Voldemort?"
"I really don't know."
"I'm more of a newcomer to Prague politics," Lukáš Kaucký, a cultural councillor, responded to the "Kmotrovský" test.
And although he is a political veteran, Councillor Karel Březina reacted similarly.
Like the term "golf hole."
"It's the only expression you give me that I sometimes use."
"I don't generally accept slang."
The editorial team chose six examples from a glossary published by Aktuálně.cz this June before the ODS electoral congress, mainly those notoriously associated with the Prague City Hall.
The socialists were to explain the terms "Voldemort", "the biggest golf hole in Prague", "go to the patisserie", "bull's neck", "treason of the capital" and "to tin".
Three of the councillors agreed with the quiz, the fourth - Antonín Weinert, who is to head Prague's education in the future - first promised the interview, but later he did not answer the phone.
The fifth alderman, Petr Dolínek, rejected the test.
"I don't care about these things at all, and I'm not going to judge how much fun the citizens' democrats are having."
"I'm now dealing with how we're going to understand each other within our programs," he responded.
As it has already been said, alderman Lukáš Kaucký would not have recognized in the headline above that the talk is about an influential businessman and friend of the exprimator Bém Roman Janoušek.
"Voldemort" doesn't say anything to Kaucký and the only term he correctly guessed in the exam is "the biggest golf hole in Prague".
"That's Blanka's tunnel," says Kaucky, and immediately adds, "but I know it more from the newspapers."
"I'm going to have to pay for a language course," he joked.
Not only matador Karel Březina, but also the environmental councilor Lukáš Plachý deciphers the golf hole as a Blanka tunnel.
Both Social Democrats then know who Voldemort really is, and Lukáš Plachý is also familiar with where to find this figure - he knows the meaning of the expression "to go to the confectioner's shop".
"I think that means going to some Prague company," Plachý is close to deciphering that it is the headquarters of Janoušek's companies.
According to Březina, he drew his knowledge from newspapers rather than using such a dictionary.
In a social democracy, according to the test participants, there is no such familiar vocabulary of slang terms.
"I've consulted with my colleagues, but it looks like we don't really have anything like that."
"We call ourselves names, sometimes abbreviations and distortions of names are used," says Petr Hulínský, the chairman of the ČSSD in Prague.
"I was called Birch in school, but I don't know if my colleagues call me Birch," admits Karel Březina.
The name has been tried and it works.
Alderman Weinert is for the party Děda or less friendly Dědek, representative Miroslav Poche, who drew attention to himself before the election fraud in sponsoring the party, with some colleagues has the nickname "Igáček".
Nicknames are also the only thing that social democrats allow in intra-party speech.
Hulínský reportedly does not like to hear Hulda, but the daily Aktuálně.cz recorded another nickname of this Prague chairman.
"Doctor of baton law" is said to remind that Petr Hulínský received his JUDr. degree at the Bratislava Police Academy.
The government wants to reduce the torture of "witches", published a booklet
Women declared witches in Burkina Faso have several common characteristics.
Rather, they belong to the older generation, they cannot engage in work, for example, for health reasons, they are single and do not have children.
The one who "becomes a witch" is sent into isolation so as not to threaten the rest of the village.
"A man's fate is seldom met."
“Young healthy women do not move away either, because they help with work and give birth to children,” describes the nun who takes care of more than a hundred women in a special house in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso.
The local government has now decided to take action against the unusual "social measure".
She has published an information booklet to help curb the witch hunt.
There's a catch.
"More than 70 percent of adults in Burkina Faso can't read," the newspaper Die Standard said.
Accusations of witchcraft are common in other African countries.
In Ghana, which borders Burkina Faso, 72-year-old Ammy Hemmah died last week after three women and two men tortured her, poured kerosene and set her on fire.
The case was reported by the BBC.
The perpetrators say it was an unfortunate coincidence.
On the woman, according to their version, the oil was ignited, which is used for ritual anointing.
The fire broke out after the group tried to “expel the evil spirit” from the woman.
Isolation of "witches" is supported by people regardless of the level of education achieved.
The newspaper Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso as saying: "The devourers of human souls have always posed a danger," he said.
In Burkina Faso, while the government is trying to moderate the witch hunt, the president himself took part in it last year.
"After his aunt's death, Gambian President Jammi unleashed a massive witch hunt that was supposed to have been involved in her death and tried to use black magic to kill the president himself."
"He enlisted the help of shamans from nearby Guinea who, accompanied by police officers, soldiers and the President's personal security, forcibly escorted randomly selected men and women from Gambian villages to the President's farm in Kanilai," Amnesty International said in its report.
On the farm, trapped people had to drink a potion of herbs with hallucinogenic effects, which additionally caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two prisoners did not survive on the farm.
After international pressure, nearly a thousand prisoners were eventually released.
Bakal's tenant: Heating in the stove, higher rent signed
An older, stocky man stepped out of the door of the client center of the company RPG Byty "uhlobaron" Zdeněk Bakala, the largest private owner of rental apartments in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm, he carried a file with new leases to three apartments: his own, his daughter’s, and his son, who is serving his sentence.
Deregulation has increased the rent for all three.
Instead of 3500 per month from next year, the son will pay CZK 4100 for the second category apartment 2+1.
"And there is no hot water, and the petrama must be heated," the man points his finger at his son's new contract, for which he has power of attorney.
"But I signed it," he explains half angry and half resigned.
The civic association BytyOKD.cz, which has described the new lease terms as "incorrect and indecent", advises tenants not to sign the new contract and wait until December 7 when it will publish instructions on how to proceed against them.
But the man just waved his hand at it.
"One says it, the other says it," he frowns.
Ostrava is becoming a great laboratory of deregulation.
After the New Year, the vast majority of apartments that still have non-market rent in the Czech Republic are waiting.
So I decided to visit the “laboratory” in person.
The Havířov RPG waiting room is one of four in the Ostrava region and on Tuesday at nine in the morning it is already full.
Next to the door is a security guard from the security agency with a summoning device.
"Rent 2011", lit a special button on its touch screen.
One tap and a number slips out of the machine.
You won't even be able to read "157" and your number is already beeping on the large display under the ceiling of the waiting room.
It's your turn in half a second.
After a while, an elderly couple comes to ask about the rent, but the rush in the waiting room obviously does not concern new rents at all.
Most people came to solve common problems as usual - requests for repairs, insurance claims, and the like.
Letters with new leases have been sent to the mailboxes of most of the 44,000 apartments in the RPG portfolio since mid-November.
In their letters, RPG Flats proposes to increase their rent by 15 to 38 percent.
A special counter for new leases was opened at the client center on November 18.
"It's been running for a week, so it's only in the running," the workers behind the counter answer after a moment of hesitation when the client introduces himself as a journalist.
Deregulation and Bakal's former mining apartments are a local hot topic.
Before the elections, the deputy speaker of the parliament and Ostrava native Lubomír Zaorálek from the ČSSD took it quite loudly, and even now the local newspapers are full of it.
"Twenty years after them, I want a new floor."
“They didn’t even change my toilet seat,” the man said.
Most of the time, according to the workers, pensioners come to see if they will get a discount from the rent if they sign on time, as the RPG promises them in a special offer.
A half discount on the February rent will also be given to other tenants who sign the new contract by December 15.
But the "deregulation" partition in Havířov is definitely not overloaded with questions.
"Of yesterday's 360 clients, only about 40 to 50 people were here for the 2011 lease," the workers behind the counter estimated.
On the web and in its bulletin boards, the RPG suggests individual contracting where necessary.
However, if both parties do not agree on the lease, it will have to be determined by an independent court.
"This is not a threat, but information about the only possible and completely legitimate legal procedure," the RPG warns on its website.
"No one will judge here," thinks one of the employees of RPG Byty, and the man on the street in front of the client center partially agrees with her.
“I have $13,000 in my pension, and I have $5,000 left to eat, and I don’t have the money to sue,” he said.
However, the worker is soon in doubt.
"We'll see."
"Mr. Zaorálek tells them in the media not to sign, so people are probably waiting," he thinks.
Rental regulation ends in most of the Czech Republic with the New Year 2011 and according to RPG Byty their increase is an economic necessity.
"The current rent still does not reach even the amount necessary for simple maintenance of the housing stock," reminds Pavel Klimeš, director of the residential portfolio of RPG Byty, that the neglect of the housing stock reproached by the angry tenant is the main reason for the increase in rents, according to homeowners.
While in five years between 2005 and 2010, RPGs could invest four billion in apartments, in four years from 2011 to 2014 it is expected to be 5.2 billion.
Meanwhile, the large screen hanging at the ceiling opposite the padded seats of the Havířov waiting room repeats several red highlighted information.
"The rent increase in 2011 of 15% or less applies to 31,200 apartments, that's more than 90% of RPG apartments."
"And it will always be the most by 7.50 CZK per square meter and month," he appears on the screen.
With only 400 apartments from the RPG portfolio, rents will increase by 38 percent.
"In these cases, it is an increase from the extremely low amount of 19.66 CZK per square meter," warns the RPG.
With 2,600 apartments, the rent will remain the same next year.
RPG Byty promises that deregulation will not drive rents by leaps and bounds, but will be spread over four to eight years.
In addition, it adds another commitment: all the money from the rent increase (see graph) will give the company back to the apartments, mainly to the thermal savings - new windows and insulation.
They should be given priority by people who sign an agreement to increase rents.
The offices include a kindergarten, the architects understood
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would expect that it also hides a mini-school with everything that goes with it - with colorful walls, imaginative furniture, a bunch of toys and even a miniature playground on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, it can be visited by children of Arch.Design employees.
Design-architectural company Arch.Design, from whose studios came a number of important Brno buildings, counted on space for its company mini-school from the very first drawings of the Avriopoint building.
It employs almost 90 people, mostly at the age of babyboom, and it was important for women designers and architects to be able to return to work quickly.
Along with the possibility of part-time work, the kindergarten is a benefit that Arch.Design offers to its employees as part of a social program.
Stavarky and architects have the opportunity to combine a demanding job with child care.
The mini-school was invented by the employees of Arch.Design themselves and with the support of the management they managed to get a subsidy from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company mini-school is financed by the European Social Fund through the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment and the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the grant funding (a subsidy of CZK 2.8 million), they were able to purchase equipment and equipment and ensure qualified staff and operation for two years.
After exhausting the financial subsidy (2 years), Arch.Design is obliged to run the mini-school at its own expense for 3 years.
The preparation of the project took one year and Economy Rating significantly helped with the application.
The care is provided by qualified staff, the children are taken care of all day by a nurse and kindergarten teacher, so children without age limit can go to kindergarten, yet most of them are over 3 years old.
Because it is a "mini-school", only 5 children can be present at the same time, but during the day there are more.
The operation of the kindergarten is flexible according to the needs of parents and children of all employees have the same right to use the kindergarten regardless of the hierarchy of position in the company.
Although it is an individual education and care, the program content in the mini-school is comparable to the framework program of preschool education.
Children not only play here, but they are also provided with quality teaching - from basic cognition to preparation for school benches, English language is also taught.
The class is equipped not only with toys, stimulating games, but also a computer that children can use.
The presence of small children in the company creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can check their child at any time and there are no stressful situations with delayed picking up of children from kindergartens away from their parents’ workplace.
Parents use their working hours more productively.
It is no wonder that there is a naturally loyal employee-employer relationship.
Arch.Design has thus become one of the Czech companies that offer significant benefits in recruiting new employees, are family-friendly and through this program has strengthened personnel marketing.
The house of bones fascinates even after 100 years. Look into the interiors by Gaudí
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the staircase resembles the backbone of a dinosaur, and the balconies are open fish mouths.
This is the Casa Batlló in Barcelona by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Thanks to its organic shapes, the house has earned the nickname House of Bones.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, tile fragments and mosaics, a facade reminiscent of scales and ubiquitous soft curves, all this is typical of the Art Nouveau of Antoni Gaudí.
The front of the house plays out dreamy lines, tender colors and textures reminiscent of nature and animals.
Detailed observation shows geometry, rhythm and a well-thought-out order.
At night, the entire facade of the house sounds even more dramatic, it is illuminated so that the impression of the brilliance of colors is even more enhanced.
The twisting and twisting of shapes appears equally in interiors.
Wood in the waves copies window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, peepholes and moldings.
House Batlló, located in the Eixample district on the busy shopping street Passeig de Gracia No. 43, was created by the reconstruction of the house from 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
Reconstruction took two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on demolishing the old building and building a completely new one, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea for an unusual and cheaper redevelopment.
Casa Batlló was not designed by Antoni Gaudí himself.
It was designed by architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on his design board that decorations were created for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the use of mosaic on the facade.
A number of other creators and artists worked on the facade.
The joint work on the designs of Casa Batlló started the successful cooperation between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol was involved in the construction of Gaudí’s Casa Milá and Park Guell, which contains Gaudí’s other works.
From the locals, the house soon after completion earned the nickname "House of Bones" thanks to its organic shapes.
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening windows, began to call it "the yawning house".
It is also said that at the top of the building is depicted the sword of St. George, the patron saint of Catalonia.
Hidden religious motifs also contain other sculptural elements of the building.
Gaudí designed for his time a unique central heating system with vents and typical chimneys.
Their forty-five degree inclination may seem bizarre.
When creating Gaudí absolutely did not respect the building regulations of the time and did not let himself be bound by them.
At the beginning of the construction, he obtained a building permit from the city, but the data on the planned reconstruction were so vague that two years later the city council was horrified by the result and asked for correction.
For example, it bothered the councilors that the building also interfered with the pillars in the public sidewalk.
On the contrary, only fifteen days after the city district’s appeal, Josep Batlló applied for (and successfully obtained) a permit to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor was a social salon and on the third floor a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented a jewelry store.
The whole six-storey house intersects the stairs, which can be climbed up to the roof terrace itself.
The essential elements of the redevelopment were the abolition of all right angles and straight lines and their replacement with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors, and the larger company can communicate with each other comfortably without retaining the privacy needed for more intimate conversations at the same time.
In addition to the new facade, the house with Gaudí’s reconstruction also received an unconventional roofing and two additional floors.
Also impressive is Gaudí's play with light, blue and white glazed tiles, with which the inner courtyard is lined, and skylights.
The game of two colors adds maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was enough to simply bet on the principle that white reflects light more than dark, which, on the contrary, absorbs the sun's rays.
Casa Batlló, which was included in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund in 2005, can be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and spectacular apartment open to the public.
The owners decided to take this step only in 2002, on the occasion of the celebration of the one hundred and fiftieth anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They stayed with the tours because they found it to be a very profitable business and in addition, they expanded the tours to include common and attic spaces, including a roof terrace.
Admission to the monument is definitely not negligible, it is 16.50 euros and students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist passes have a 20% discount.
The amount far exceeds the price of admission to Gaudí's other buildings in the city.
If you want to taste the true atmosphere of a house with dragon turrets, you need to quickly make friends with one of the residents of the apartment building and visit it right at home.
How to choose a mattress and grate: women have different requirements than men
Not a flashy bed frame, but the quality of the lying surface, that is, mattresses and grate, give the basis for a really good bed.
However, they must be harmoniously complemented to suit a particular user.
When choosing, a lot of things decide, from weight, height, age, health and gender of the owner.
Also important is the type of interior in which mattresses and grate are purchased.
Typical example?
For example, on weekend cottages, where it is not regularly heated, latex mattresses are not suitable, because they heat up more slowly.
In addition, they have a significantly higher weight than standard polyurethane mattresses.
They need to be turned around regularly.
If they do not have a lot of vents in the core, and they are still on a solid board, they retain moisture: Mold could also appear under them.
The choice is also made by habit.
Those who have spent a long time abroad, where very high mattresses with a softening layer are often used, will hardly feel good on a low and hard surface.
"I think all the hockey players who were coming back from the NHL complained to me that they wouldn't sleep here."
"For their battered shoulders, heels and hips, they needed mattresses with a softening layer of lazy foam."
"These are recommended even for people with diabetes who have a nervous system disorder, so they do not receive "information" from the joints and skin," explains Sylva Hadamczik, who specializes in upholstered furniture.
Many hockey players, but also other customers, were looking for a mattress with lazy foam years ago.
"Today it's okay, suitable mattresses have Tempur, Italian Magniflex, but also Czech Tropico."
You don't have to be an NHL player to appreciate lazy foam.
This "miracle" works simply.
It optimizes its rigidity and shape according to the absorbed heat, or adapts to your warm body.
There is no pressure, you will not roll over at night like after a hard match.
You'll just sleep better.
Lazy foam also works as a protection against bedsores.
When choosing the size of the mattress, add the length of the foot to your height, which is usually about 21 to 34 cm.
Both a man and a woman with a height of about 180 cm need a bed of 210 to 220 cm.
The minimum width for one should be 90 cm for a double bed, a total of 180 cm.
For single beds, for example for singles, a minimum of 120 to 140 cm is recommended.
For comfort and a visit.
"Otherwise, the rule for the width of the bed is simple: when lying on your back, you should have your hands comfortably slightly bent in your elbow," advises Ing. Helena Prokopová, a guildmaster of the Association of Upholsterers and Decorators, who has been dealing with the issue of healthy sleeping and ergonomics of furniture for many years and lectures it at vocational schools.
For a double bed, everyone needs their own grid and mattress, but here, be careful when buying to align the heights of the mattresses.
Otherwise, there will be nothing left but to mount the grids to different heights, but you may not be able to do this with every bed frame.
Foam mattresses should have a height of at least 14 cm, types with a spring skeleton of at least 15, of which at least three centimeters count on the shaping and loosening layer.
"When touching your hands or sitting on the mattress, you definitely must not feel the springs," warns Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a certain type of grid.
Upholstered beds, when the mattress and the base are like conjoined Siamese twins, have nothing to do in the bedrooms.
Mattresses do not ventilate well, you can not wash their cover, which is already common today.
And because we normally sweat 0.2 to 0.75 liters per night, it is clear that after five to seven years the mattress will begin to resemble one large (and clogged) sieve.
That is why experts reject advertising slogans about the life of mattresses up to 25 years, or even a lifetime warranty.
However, everything has its ale.
That’s why we offer practical advice from sellers: for mattresses with a width of 120 or 140 cm, do not give up hygiene and washable coating, but rather add a mattress protector that you can easily remove and wash.
Although mattress covers are commonly produced today with zippers around the perimeter, so after opening we get two parts (very important for washing and washing machine size!), yet handling in larger types (and one person) while shooting could resemble a light weight fight in the ring with a heavy one.
Do you have a solid board in your bed instead of a grid?
Never!
Maximum for a one-night stay.
However, provide the plate (if it does not already have them) with ventilation holes and use a mattress with a spring frame and a height of at least 15 cm with springs in bags (from it.Taschenfederkern) and a loosening layer.
Polyurethane mattress does not belong on such a substrate.
For non-positioning slats with 14 to 18 slats, latex or sandwich mattresses will be suitable (for example, a combination of latex and coconut), but you will always pay for slats with more slats, 28 or more, where the slats in the lumbar area are doubled and their rigidity can be regulated.
The positioning lamella grids do not include spring-framed mattresses, as they do not respond to positioning.
In addition to adjusting the stiffness of the slats, you can also indulge in the so-called shoulder cradle.
This is a special slat mount that allows you to push or even tilt the slat so that the shoulder sleeps nicely "damaged".
For men who have "shoulders over their whole back", definitely an important thing.
It is even remembered by manufacturers of mattresses, who in the "men's" began to use the softening zone just in the shoulder area.
Women are also remembered - they in turn give a softer surface in the places of the hips.
For the most demanding customers are designed wing or plate grids with so-called multi-torque suspension.
The pressure decomposes into multiple points and the tension decreases.
However, be careful, as soon as you apply the wrong pillow on the right mattress and grate (large and "stuffed"), most of the "plus" disappears.
The basic rule is simple: the pillow should support the head and only reach the shoulders with the tips so that the shoulder muscles can relax.
As a suitable size is recommended 50 x 60 cm, which they prefer, for example, in Scandinavia.
When lying on the side, the pillow should align (along with the shoulder cradle of the grate or the softened zone in the mattress) the height of the shoulder.
Modern mattresses have something in common with the original straws filled with grass.
Their manufacturers are increasingly using natural materials or at least additives.
It is also a trend in mattresses.
Raw materials from oil, from which polyurethane foams are made, are replaced with natural oils, for example, from jumper and soy.
Soybeans are used by all well-known manufacturers.
"Bio in mattresses means that the core is made of a material of purely natural origin," explains Petr Vašíček from Tropico Plus.
Natural substances are also used in the production of mattress covers, one of the first was aloe vera.
But you can also indulge in microcapsules to release the fresh scent of the forest or lavender.
There is also a division between men and women.
While a man "cools" the plant extract from the birch tree, so that the mattress cover absorbs heat and cools the body, women, on the contrary, the covers "melt".
Red pepper extract increases blood circulation, making it warmer for the weaker sex.
Today's favorites?
Mattress made of cold foam (it has larger pores with broken cell structure, it is more breathable than conventional polyurethane and offers better elasticity.
Combining different stiffnesses of cold foams and "lazy" foams, multi-zone mattresses are created, which know exactly where the head, hips and heels should be.
For a quality mattress you will pay from seven thousand crowns and above.
Those that meet the health parameters have a lower VAT rate, they are taken as medical aids.
Gumotex was the first to achieve this advantage in the Czech Republic.
Saving on a mattress and grate is not easy.
Sometimes you can use the actions of manufacturers or sellers who offer two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers a Duofreeze mattress with memory foam sewn into the cover for CZK 11,990.
The second one can be bought for free.
The era of lazy or viscoelastic foams with open cell structure and high density was started by the "cosmic" Tempur material.
It was originally created as a material for NASA, because during the launches, the astronauts were subjected to enormous overload.
Tempur softens in the heat, while it hardens in the cold.
The warm human body adapts and distributes its pressure optimally.
It is therefore ideal against bedsores, but also for increased comfort when sleeping.
Viscoelastic foams are used not only for mattresses, but also for medical products, such as special pillows under the feet, which lighten the legs and the venous system.
Domestic manufacturers use, for example, foam Eucatherm C or Twinsaver and the like.
More and more parents want to monitor their children
Fear for your own child is driving more and more people to the idea of watching over GPS.
The system originally created for searching for cars can also track the movement of people, and thus help in such cases as the disappearance of nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device is about as big as a matchbox, but soon it can only be as big as a watch.
Many people were frightened by the case of the missing Anička and began to search for ways to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of violating their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not spying, but another means to reduce the likelihood that a tragedy will happen," says Petr Pilin from Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of surveillance devices to the Czech market.
"I admit that in some cases such devices can be misused, for example when they are put in the bag of someone who does not know about it, but we have not yet encountered such a case."
“For the most part, customers actually buy it for safety reasons,” added Pilin.
According to him, the child should always know for what purpose the "box" is used and how it is used in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if a child does not want to wear something like this, he will simply get rid of it.
“Even very young children are very creative in how they intentionally lose things when they don’t want to be in control.”
"High expectations were previously raised by parents' mobile phones, which can be turned off just like these tracking devices," Bočková said.
It is also questionable whether such a device would actually help in the event of an attack.
"As far as the abduction is concerned, the perpetrator will virtually always ensure that the child does not carry any electronics that could reveal his location."
"Now it's a phone."
"When tracking devices start to expand, they will look for them as well, because their sales will certainly be supported by massive advertising."
"In this case, criminals will always be one step ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
However, he admits that a similar device can help in the event of an unexpected attack by a pedophile.
According to Robert Čech from RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, even if the tracking device is destroyed immediately after the attack, his presence can help.
"The device can be set to periodically send location after a certain period of time."
"If it is damaged, at least the last location of the person concerned will be available."
"More expensive devices have built-in tiltometers, so even if a person just slipped and remained motionless, the device will immediately send a warning with an indication of position," says Čech.
According to him, a similar service can also be taken by smart mobile phones with navigation, where it is enough to upload special software.
The problem with the current tracking units is that they are either matchbox-sized devices or smaller mobile phones.
They are always at risk of losing it.
According to Pilin from Macro Weil, the device is now being tested as a regular digital watch.
"This will have the greatest advantage in that a potential aggressor may not recognize the tracking device at all."
"Or he will recognize them after some time and that can give the police extra time," he adds.
Whether the trackers develop into bracelets or pendants, they will still use the same technology used to monitor cars.
It is a combination of GPS location detection (which uses conventional car navigation) and the function of a mobile phone that reports the current position of the car.
The army has incendiary cords that would envelop the Czech Republic. But it will last only two years
The Czech army bought 445 kilometers of lines, which are used to detonate explosives.
Last year, the Ministry of Defense delivered 224 kilometers of lines to the warehouses.
