A longer index finger than a ring finger indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men who have an index finger longer than their ring finger are at a lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by the British Journal of Cancer.
It may be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the finger can serve as a simple test for prostate cancer risk, especially for men under 60," said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should undergo a prostate cancer test, especially when combined with genetic risk or other risk factors such as family health burden, Eeles added.
Between 1994 and 2009, she and her colleagues in the UK followed more than 1,500 prostate cancer patients and more than 3,000 healthy men at the same time.
More than half of the participants in the study had an index finger on their right hand that was shorter than a ring finger.
They had the same probability of prostate cancer as 19 percent of those whose fingers were the same length.
However, for those with an index finger longer than their ring finger, the risk dropped by 33 percent, and for men under 60, the risk dropped by 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers - formed in the prenatal period - seems to reflect the different levels of sex hormones to which the baby is exposed in the womb.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that testosterone promotes the growth of prostate cancer.
Professor Václav Pačes, a leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, told the Czech News Agency that he was familiar with the study, but did not believe that the relationship between finger length and cancer was "fully proven".
