Support for democracy in Latin America is growing, as is support for private enterprise.
Crime is more important than unemployment.
And Brazil considers many regions more influential than the United States.
These are some of the results of the current Latinobarómetro survey, which took place in 18 countries and was published exclusively in The Economist magazine.
Since the survey has been held regularly since 1995, it can track changes in attitudes across the entire area.
This year’s survey, which took place in September and early October, is dominated by two related issues.
The first is that Latin America is in a rather cheerful mood.
The second is to increase the stability of attitudes towards democracy and its key institutions.
Support for democracy in several Pacific Rim countries has increased significantly in South America (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has increased from a minimum of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also grew in Mexico, where the economy was recovering after a deep decline in output last year.
But only about half of those polled in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous regions, are convinced Democrats, which pulls down the regional average (see Figure 2).
About 44% of respondents across the region expressed satisfaction with the way democracy works in their country in practice, this is the same number as last year, but compared to 2001, when it was 25%, it is a large increase (Figure 3).
Roughly 34% said they trust the Assembly in their country and 45% trust the government, again the same numbers as last year, but this is a big difference compared to 2003 (17% and 24%).
Ten years ago, the economic crisis undermined democracy in Latin America.
Support came about during the global financial crisis probably because many Latin American countries suffered only a brief recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, a stronger social security network has helped to protect poor people.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty increased only marginally in 2009 and fell again to 32 percent that year.)
However, the mood changes in a wide range from country to country (see Figure 4).
Brazil’s strong economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, are reflected in a widely accepted sense of progress.
This situation is more rare in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more severe and the state of violent crime worsened.
For the second time since surveys began, more respondents across Latin America see crime as the most important issue rather than unemployment (see Chart 5).
Roughly 31% say that either they or their close relatives fell victim to crime last year, but this is down from 38% last year and is also the lowest figure since 1995.
More massive economic performance is reflected in growing support for private business and the market economy: approximately 71% of respondents across the region say that private business is essential for development, this percentage increased from 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
About 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow their country to develop, this percentage increased from 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela share the same view (and 80% support private business there), although their left-wing president Hugo Chávez expropriates many private companies.
Brazil is the leading country in the region, as mentioned by 19% of respondents (compared to 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, compared to last year unchanged) and Venezuela (9%, compared to 11% last year)
However, the United States is considered the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, with Venezuela enjoying success in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
