Microbes with arsenic resistance increase the possibility of new types of life on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients expands the scope for finding new forms of life on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Researchers have discovered an unusual bacterium here on Earth and claim it is a sign that life has options that stand outside the main elements that have been considered and essential until now.
"This organism has a dual ability."
"It can grow either through phosphorus or arsenic."
“This fact is very strange, but it doesn’t prove that this is some form of truly ‘alien’ life,” said Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report, which appeared Thursday in the online edition of the journal Science.
For a long time it was considered necessary for life six main elements - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
However, researchers have found that bacteria found in Mono Lake, California, are able to continue growing after phosphorus is replaced with arsenic.
"You'll be amazed at what's still possible," said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, a co-author of the report.
This finding is significant for the search for life beyond Earth, as researchers must be able to recognize life and know what life might look like, Anbar said.
The study focuses on microbes found on Earth.
However, a report of this novelty published to discuss it, which did not reveal the details of the finding, has sparked widespread speculation on the Internet that the report reveals the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
That's not the case.
The discovery "shows that other planetary organisms may be able to harness other elements that drive biochemistry and that a set of elements that we consider 'standard' may not be so absolutely necessary for life," explained Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
"This work is unusual because it shows the replacement of one element by another in basic biochemistry and biochemical structure," Cockell added.
It wasn't a random find.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA’s Astrobiology Institute, who led the study, focused on Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically very similar elements, so she considered that a microbe that is exposed to both elements may be able to replace one for the other.
"Arsenic is poisonous mainly because its chemical behavior is very similar to phosphorus."
"As a result, organisms can be very difficult to separate these elements from each other."
"However, arsenic is so different that just like phosphorus does not work. When it gets into the body, it begins to work in biochemical processes," explained Anbar.
Scientists collect bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and expose them to an increasing concentration of arsenic, which the bacteria are able to adapt and grow.
Microbes grow better when exposed to phosphorus, but since they can also survive with arsenic replacement, the possibility increases that a life form that uses arsenic can occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, stated that the idea of arsenic, which could be replaced with phosphorus, is not new, but there has never been an example on which this fact could be proved.
Arsenic was more common in earlier times on Earth, she said, and so scientists speculated that it may have been used by earlier life forms.
"This suggests that there may have been other ways to create life, not just the way it formed in the early Earth period," said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institute of Health.
