Attorneys for the Justice Department cleared Senator John Ensign of criminal charges related to his affair with a former campaign adviser and his efforts to secure the lobby, the senator's lawyers announced on Wednesday.
The decision ends the most serious legal threat that Mr. Ensign, a Nevada Republican, faced and who was, until the time of the scandal, considered a possible Republican presidential candidate for 2012. His affair made national headlines and damaged his career.
Mr Ensign's office said he was "certainly pleased" with the decision, which followed almost a year of investigation.
The senator could still face disciplinary action at the Senate Ethics Committee.
Mr. Ensign's lawyers said the Justice Department "has informed us that Senator Ensign will no longer be the target of the investigation and that there is no plan to bring any further charges against him in this matter."
The Justice Department declined to comment on the case.
The decision came as a surprise to many ethical lawyers outside the Justice Department, who argued that there was substantial evidence that Mr Ensign was preparing a violation of the federal lobbying ban.
Interviews, emails, and other documents that were published in the October 2009 New York Times reported that Mr. Ensign was helping Douglas Hampton, one of his assistants, secure a lucrative lobby that was to lead to the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator's affair with her.
Mrs. Hampton once worked as a treasurer in the Ensigna campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political backers to find work for Mr. Hampton and supported their views after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them, so much are the documents and interviews.
As Hampton had been Mr. Ensign's assistant until recently, he was barred from lobbying his former employer or the Senate for a year by law.
Ethics experts say the unusual settlement of Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were friends before the affair, appeared in violation of the lobbying ban.
From the evidence that was released "it became clear that this was a clear case of preparation for a violation of the law," said Stanley Brand, a Washington, D.C. lawyer who specializes in defending clients who are being investigated by the government.
While Justice Department officials refused to explain the reasons for the decision in Senator Ensign's case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said the department was cautious about political lawsuits after a large number of setbacks, including last year's decision to suspend the lawsuit against former Senator Ted Stevens amid charges of prosecutorial misconduct.
Federal prosecutors have "clearly concealed weapons," said Melanie Sloan, executive director of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a advocacy group that filed several complaints against Mr Ensign in the case.
"It basically shows that high-ranking government officials are not covered by the law," she added.
Paul Coggins, Mr. Ensign's chief lawyer, told him in an interview that he had been called by the Attorney General of the Department of Justice on Monday and then the next day, and told him that the Department had found no charges against his client.
Mr Ensign's defense team is working with prosecutors to try to convince them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement on Wednesday, "acted in accordance with the law."
Mr Coggins refused to specify the legal arguments he had forwarded to the prosecutors.
"I'm not comfortable recounting the details of my discussions with the Department of Justice except that we think they made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to halt an investigation into a separate complaint in which an ethics group filed allegations that payment of Ensign's parents to the Hamptons of $96,000 violated federal electoral law.
The election commission said it did not have enough evidence to prove that the money meant anything other than a gift.
One company for which Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton find a lobbying job was NV Energy, a major Nevada corporation that had long supported the Senator.
A December 2008 e-mail showed that after Mr. Hampton began to work in the company as a lobbyist, the head of Mr. Ensign's staff - John Lopez - communicated with Mr. Hampton, telling him that he was "pounding" to the Home Office on the subject being discussed.
Mr. Ensign also attended a luncheon with Mr. Hampton and another Nevadan client, Allegiant Air, and called on the Minister of Transportation to arrange a meeting on behalf of the airline after they hired Mr. Hampton for lobbying work.
When news of the affair first surfaced last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned as the fourth Republican leader in the Senate.
After many months of stagnation, Mr. Ensign told reporters two weeks ago that he planned to participate in a third term in the Senate.
In a report that Mr. Ensign is no longer the target of the criminal investigation, his spokeswoman Jennifer Cooper said the senator hoped the ethics committee would quickly follow the Department of Justice and end the entire investigation.
"Senator Ensign looks forward to continuing his hard work on behalf of the Nevada people," she continued.
