They argued that the media constantly fanned the flames of emotion over the case.
"The daily rush of media, cameras and reporters in court," the lawyer wrote, "was something that has never been seen here in New Haven before, and it may also be a national rarity."
Their focus on Twitter is controversial.
In the interviews, some journalists argued that the immediate reporting was more outrageous than the reports given later, and from their point of view, the judicial police should direct the field of action of the other trials.
But some lawyers have demanded appellate courts with frequently used arguments that social and technological changes require the courts to adapt.
Mr. Hayes' lawyers are pursuing this right.
In their archives, they referred to the Supreme Court's 1966 decision on Dr. Sheppard's sentence, due to the breadth of the proceedings, and wanted to clarify the requirement that new media require new rules.
"This case," they wrote, "represents the case of Sheppard versus Maxwell of the 21st century."
Can civility overcome the chasm?
After a campaign that was notable for its offensiveness and negativity, a small amount of politeness emerged in Washington this week.
Is this the first swallow of real cooperation between two political parties or just an illusory moment before a quick return to the party struggle in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and parliamentary leaders has yielded no major breakthroughs on the crucial issues that need to be discussed during the session.
In any case, however, it was a polite discussion dealing with the differences of opinion between the two parties, as well as defining their common responsibilities, rather than another empty episode of party strife.
Wednesday's public session of the President's Deficit Commission was also civilized, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that close cooperation for several months has built up a mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap that still divides members.
And it is quite difficult to say that a new era of cooperation has begun.
The two sides are now in a probationary period - probing each other for signs of collegiality and compromise, while trying to assess the boundaries of public opinion and voter patience towards a renewed party war.
Therefore, Tuesday's hearing and its subsequent evaluation by the participants were conducted with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too wide and too deep to suggest a rapid change in the conditions that have prevailed here for the past two years.
Whether it’s about taxes, spending, health care or rights, both sides are miles away.
However, the November elections were prepared by Washington at least quickly.
"It's not a question of whether regulatory issues have changed," said Pete Wehner, Bush's administrator, now at the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
“They are inevitable after the election.
The election aroused the emotions of the party members, and then they were quiet.
It's good."
On several issues, particularly those to be discussed at the meeting, Republicans and Democrats have little chance of finding a solution.
Bush's tax cut expired at the end of the year, and no one considers it favorable.
Both sides want to find a way to protect some or all of them, permanently or temporarily.
Like the likely compromise on unemployment benefits just because Republicans can’t watch them support tax cuts for the wealthy while refusing unemployment benefits to the unemployed.
After the White House meeting on Tuesday, there is already more optimism about a possible agreement on these issues, along with the ratification of the new inaugural treaty.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution cautions that successful cooperation on major issues will not necessarily lead to a two-party relationship when the 112th Congress convenes for January.
Rather, a period of disagreement is likely, or even inevitable, he said.
"Once the things that need to be done are done, psychology will return to one of the confrontations in the short term," he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism - which is largely widespread - that politeness would lead them to actually cooperate.
"I look at all the events between now and 2012 as a shadow box, when the main events will take place in 2012," he said.
The reasons are largely related to the build-up of the new Republican majority in the White House and the voters of the tea parties who helped create it.
Republican leaders now face the danger of exaggeration, they know they must act on their promises, and they must cut government spending and repeal the new health care bill.
These partisan lines are clear in the initial responses to the deficit recommendations, which include reforming the tax code and raising some taxes, raising the retirement age, and cutting spending.
Joint chairmen Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult tasks in Washington, and they have, in their opinion, put pressure on the deficit issue to the public agenda in ways that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in an 18-member committee to present their plan as an official recommendation and fight to get as close to that number as possible.
The biggest opposition is among the elected officials on the jury, who suggest that, in the case of financial issues, we have, at least today, little groundwork or the will to compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the White House and parliamentary Republicans.
The first will begin next year in the form of party conflicts, when Republicans will call on Obama to address the budget, taxes, and health care, followed by a period of greater party cooperation.
What causes the shift?
Public opinion.
There is plenty of evidence that, despite the partisanship at the last election, most Americans still want to see two parties working together.
If it could go to a stalemate, as it did in 1995, then both sides will be watching the public’s reactions very closely.
Whoever is threatened with a reduction in votes is likely to change course and seek a compromise.
This can be an optimistic view of things.
Partyism and regulation are larger today than they were in the mid-1990s, and it turns out that there has been a greater ideological divide between Obama and the parliamentary Republicans than there has been with the Republicans and Bill Clinton.
At the same time, activists on both sides see 2010 as a prelude to more important elections in 2012.
Based on this reality, the courtesy that emerged this week would be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will take a lot of effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
