"Everybody here loves that moka."
"He was a good leader and took care of his people," said Sreng Kor Ma, 42.
Known as a "butcher" for his brutality during the Khmer Rouge rule, the commander remains popular in this remote Khmer Rouge possession in northwestern Cambodia, where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure and where thousands of former Khmer Rouge soldiers still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge relinquished power, long-standing loyalty is also being eroded in Anlong Veng.
In April, victims of the Truth and Reconciliation Forum were allowed to publicly confront people who were part of the regime.
In June, the government provided textbooks that for the first time explain to children the history of the Khmer Rouge and their former soldiers.
And in July, the UN and the Cambodian court jointly bring the first conviction of a former Khmer Rouge member, the sentence of the former leader, the notorious Tuol Sleng violent association, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Ghost, to 35 years in prison.
With each such advance, unrest grew among Khmer Rouge veterans in Anlong Veng, complicating reconciliation efforts and their attempts to re-enter Cambodian society.
"There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge, but they are powerless to do anything," said Chhang Youk, head of the documentation center of Cambodia, an independent organization that studies the regime.
"For them, life among the Khmer Rouge was wonderful, but the regime became a symbol of evil."
"It divides families."
During the Khmer Rouge rule in Cambodia, from 1975 to 1979, an estimated 1.7 million people were executed or died of starvation, illness or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot government in 1979, the remnants of the regime and its soldiers fled to the Cambodian border with Thailand.
There they launched an uprising that lasted until the last movement in December 1998.
Pol Pot, Nuon Chea, and Ieng Sary waged guerrilla warfare from their bases in the mountains and jungles of western Cambodia, while Ta Mok cultivated followers in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace agreement, the country was led to its first democratic elections in 1993. Large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to transition to a government that culminated in the surrender of Ieng Sara in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who persisted, was captured by government forces in the nearby Dangrek Mountains in 1999.
He died in Phnom Penh prison in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Their patrons no longer cared for them, most of the former Khmer Rouge fighters have fallen into ordinary Cambodian rural life, and many of them nostalgically reminisce about the time of the movement.
Although several elite Khmer Rouge have maintained their local government position in exchange for their weapons, their position remains weak, as unskilled farmers.
"These people have benefited minimally from the surrender," said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which runs public forums throughout Cambodia, including Anlong Veng.
"They are surrounded by the utopian agrarian ideology of the regime."
"They were raised without any idea of making a trade."
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle around Anlong Veng before settling down as a poor farmer in 1998.
"Life under the Khmer Rouge was good," he said.
"The Mok has fed everyone."
"But now life is hard because we have to make everything ourselves."
