The software suggests improvements in vehicles in real time.
Since Red Bull entered the Formula 1 series in 2004, its history in this extraordinary world of speed has been characterised by surprise and success.
At first, no one took the possibilities of this newly arrived team too seriously, and despite the upward trend of recent times, everyone was betting on the triumph of Ferrari Fernando Alonso.
Without wanting to diminish the driving ability of the champion, German Sebastian Vettel, or the Renault engine that powers his car, a legend was born in the world of Formula One - the "secret weapon" that the multi-ethnic Siemens has put in the hands of Red Bull to make it a winning team.
In fact, it is a powerful software simulating marches, which the German company launched in 2007 for purposes very far removed from automobile sport.
The so-called PLM, this powerful software device, has been used to design assembly lines in production plants around the world, in power plants and for high-precision instruments.
Its aim is to faithfully reproduce the product or simulate the process before it is actually created, thus avoiding unnecessary mistakes and expenses.
PLM facilitated the development of Canon cameras, Sukhoi aircraft and Nissan’s most famous commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of Siemens’ industrial division, explains that the use of this software enabled the Red Bull team to carry out “in a matter of hours, in near real time” modifications and improvements that would otherwise be detected during races and trials.
Russwurm says that in 1992, the stables employed an average of 10 technicians who were able to make a maximum of three or four improvements in a single period.
Today, the Red Bull team employs 180 young highly qualified professionals equipped with powerful information technology to analyze and design every type of modification of racing vehicles.
The head of Siemens explained that the PLM software is able to analyze and improve all elements of Red Bull racing vehicles, except for the engine, for which Renault is fully responsible.
Materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety features are modified.
Changes can be converted from virtual reality to reality in less than 24 hours thanks to advanced laser manufacturing systems and high-tech autoclaves.
The only limit to this technical achievement is $40 million, which is the maximum that each Formula 1 team can spend for each period to improve their competitiveness.
Red Bull has set up a high-tech plant 50km from London to design and manufacture its racing cars.
These are two buildings that are restricted to visitors - especially journalists.
Everything that happens here is considered a "big secret".
The list of participants in this project includes 580 people, including two pilots - champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
The hero of Red Bull is Formula One champion Sebastian Vettel.
However, behind the immense technological means that the energy drinks brand has put into its participation in the race circuits, there are other protagonists whose help is invaluable, and yet no one knows them.
Production technology chief Steve Nevey said five years ago it was possible to say that advances in vehicle research and development contributed 50% to the victory, and the rest was thanks to the riders.
Currently, this ratio has changed and the technology is worth 85% of the achievements, while the pilots contribute 15%.
Nevey acknowledges that Vettel or Webber will never be replaced by computing, as they are "unpredictable gladiators".
