Zapatero and the Red German Line
Berlin decided to keep the euro, but set the conditions for the whole Union.
Tensions in the markets have provoked a double government response.
On the one hand, José Luis Zapatero proposed new adaptation measures, from reducing taxes for small and medium-sized enterprises, through the regulation of private placement agencies or the abolition of 426 euros for the unemployed without benefits, to the privatisation of 49% of AENA (Spanish Airports and Air Traffic Control - note), the administrator of Barajas and El Prat airports and 30% of the state lottery.
On the other hand, Vice-President Elena Salgado, with the support of former Prime Minister Felipe González, joined the criticisms of Chancellor Angela Merkel over her responsibility for unleashing the current crisis.
How to interpret these movements?
Let it be said in advance that Merkel’s position is not a mistake in her communication policy.
On the contrary, it is another point in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And here Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which alludes to the idea of upholding the old traditions held by a large part of the other members.
In the face of European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first of these is a strong eurozone, which would include Germany, but also Austria and the Netherlands, while the southern states would leave the currency zone.
The second is a return to the brand - although now it may seem like scifi, this version has wide public support, approaching 50% of the population.
The third option, according to German proposals, is to recast the euro with more macroeconomic surveillance, budgetary rigour, fines for guilty states, possible deferrals of payments for some of them, and an extension of the possible costs of regulation to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been defined for some time, so there is no room for tricks now.
First, when both the International Monetary Fund and the European Commission incited deficits in 2009, the German government pulled constitutional reform off its sleeve to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of a contradiction between what Germany thought was right (the plans for fiscal austerity and the stability of public finances) and what its European partners, including France, practiced.
The second was shown by this Central European country, when Merkel painfully dragged forward the decision to save Greece.
Even then it was the subject of harsh criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public opinion, which was also published, were strongly opposed to saving Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel once again appeared with a clear position when she demanded to reform the European Union's conventions in order to allow the rescue of a member state, while at the same time making private creditors liable to bear part of the costs.
This position was interpreted as anti-European, as it accelerated the Irish crisis and everything else.
However, its proposal, albeit in a somewhat relaxed form, has been approved, and over the coming months we should follow the Union's reform process, which should allow for these measures from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line, which it does not intend to cross.
And he tells all of us that although there is now a need to take measures with which he seems to disagree too much, from that date the old functioning of the euro will be over.
2013 will mark the birth of a new currency zone, in which rule-breaking states will be severely sanctioned and may be forced to announce deferred payments, and the private sector will also have to bear some of the costs.
Germany is telling us that we need to take a tough path of growth with increased savings and investment, moderate consumption, improved productivity and competitiveness, and capital reserves.
They simply do not want to tolerate another option based on debt and building, with huge gaps in the balance of payments that prevailed during the boom in Spain’s growth.
The offer is clear.
And we'd make a mistake if we didn't understand.
This is not just about restoring the public deficit to 3% in 2013.
What they want from us is much tougher.
And worst of all, under these circumstances, we could be wrong ourselves.
I hope that these current turbulences will give way to more calm.
And we will take advantage of the opportunity that they are giving us until spring 2013.
