Sport and circumvention of rules
Fints like Alonso and Ramos showed in the match against Ajax show wit, not intent on escaping punishment.
The alleged expulsion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the Champions League match against Ajax on 23 November caused a sea of ink to be put out about whether or not this is unsportsmanlike behavior and whether UEFA should eventually punish both footballers.
As is known, a few minutes before the end of the match (which had their team clearly won), the named players one by one deliberately lost time at the moment when the foul was to be played to provoke the referee, and he showed them a second yellow card.
In this way, both players will fulfill the prescribed penalty in the next match against Auxerre - with Real Madrid finishing in their group lead - and will be able, deprived of cards, to proceed to the next stage.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee awarded coach José Mourinho a two-match penalty and the guilty players were fined cash.
Provocation of the yellow card under similar conditions is not a new practice, but is more or less common in football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos of football, i.e. rules that are unwritten, but are being followed.
Part of the discussion in this case was due to the fact that it was attended by the Real Madrid team (which boasts generosity and honor in its anthem, and which has already fined its players for similar actions), and it seems also thanks to the dramatization led by Mourinho, who thus adds another episode to his long history as a comedian and provocateur.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of conduct, which is not expressly prohibited by the rules, is contrary to the principles of sport, that is, whether there is circumvention of the law in these acts; these are indeed actions respecting the rules of sport, the meaning of which, however, seems to be trying to circumvent.
What kind of harm is caused by such actions?
One of the elements of sportsmanship is the physical inviolability of opponents, which was not violated in these cases, i.e. there was no violent play.
Another of these prerequisites for a clean game is to avoid allowing players to have an advantage over the opponent's team due to their offense - which did not happen here either.
Thus, the paradoxical thing about Real Madrid players’ actions is that what we normally characterize as a ruse or circumvention of the law did not occur, there was no hidden violation of the rules in order to avoid sanctions, but this behavior should have been as visible as possible in order to receive the punishment.
They waited and liked to be punished.
Another question, however, is what advantage the culprits will have from their intentional misdemeanor.
Here it is necessary to state that the opponent does not get into a disadvantaged position, and that there will be no gain in the current match, because the obvious consequence is that the team itself will have fewer players.
And this is not a useful strategy for the next match, as the club will not be able to count on these players.
The advantage obviously lies in the fact that players start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could jeopardize their participation in the future match.
However, this is an advantage from a long-term perspective and with a certain degree of uncertainty, i.e. at first glance the team can be eliminated, and in addition, by this action the players will get rid of the penalty, and pass to the second round of cards, in which one card less than in the first round is enough to be eliminated.
So as the rounds continue, it will not be entirely clear whether this is an advantage.
In short, these negotiations do not go against the sporting spirit, which includes making strategic decisions that will allow maximum benefit within the rules.
in the case we are dealing with here, the players did not aim to avoid a penalty (which would be a clear case of circumvention of the rules), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without evading punishment or running away from it.
Although the line between ingenuity and circumvention of the rules is not entirely clear, I believe that in this case it was definitely ingenuity.
It seems to me that the controversy arises for two reasons: because it was two self-exclusions and because of the way in which the instructions to provoke them from the leadership were carried out.
Damage to sporting principles by such actions is not as ethical as aesthetic.
