U.S. Changes Visa Rules
People will have to contact the Visa Application Service Centers before the Consular Department interview; the costs will be lower and the waiting time will be reduced.
As of January 10, 2011, the visa process at the United States Embassy and Consulates will change.
with the new procedure, most applicants will have to contact the Visa Application Services Centres (abbreviated from ASC English) before the interview at the Consular Department.
The personnel from the ASC will remove the biometric information of the applicant and it will be evaluated by the Consular Department before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, including the following:
The total cost of handling the visa will be lower, there will be no need to pay a fee for arranging a meeting, a second for processing the application and another for delivery of the document by the shipping service.
The applicant will pay only one fee to cover all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: an amount equivalent to $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa applications (including temporary worker visas), and $390 for a visa for merchants and investors.
People who want to renew their visa will not have to have an interview with a consular officer, but will only contact the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and have their fingerprints taken.
Since the biometric information will be removed at the ASC, applicants who will require a second appointment with an interview at the Consular Department will spend a shorter time here than in the past.
Similarly, those who apply for a visa at the consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an extra $26 service fee.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following website http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
