World Plan for Lighting Restoration
The United Nations has proposed a plan in Cancun to restore home lighting, shop lighting and industrial space in 100 countries with the aim of achieving a reduction in the greenhouse effect (GES), which corresponds to almost one-third of the additional limitation that needs to be achieved to stabilize the planet’s climate from now until 2020.
This ambitious plan is at the stage of major concrete projects that the UN wants to push through in Cancún to compensate for the absence of difficult-to-implement reduction commitments on the part of industrialised countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if we replace incandescent bulbs that monopolize 50 to 70% of the market with fluorescent or, even better, light-emitting diode (DEL) bulbs, a significant amount of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GES emissions on the planet generated by lighting would be degraded.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of the world’s emissions.
That’s equivalent to 70% of the world’s car fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, large countries with a significant share of emissions such as the United States, China, Europe and others, among them Canada, engaged in voluntary reduction plans that should allow global GES emissions to fall from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But 5 Gt will have to be subtracted from this balance in order to achieve a 2 degrees Celsius stabilization of climate heating by 2020 in order to exclude that it will not get out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat, and the rest, i.e. 5%, is the product of light.
With fluo-compact bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with new bulbs with DEL, we will reduce this consumption twice more.
Fluo-compact bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new DEL light bulbs, such as the one launched by Philips this week - the company reportedly participated in a UN study - have an estimated lifespan of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a incandescent light bulb, giving us an idea of the possible savings with a replacement plan that would be applied in 100 countries.
All these new bulbs can also work with rheostats and emit less heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about fluo-compact bulbs because they contain mercury and need to be classified as hazardous waste, which is still not possible in developing countries unless manufacturers set up collection centres.
However, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not a fluo-compact light bulb, but rather thermal coal-fired power plants, which emit much of the mercury needed to produce electricity wasted in incandescent light bulbs.
In the United States alone, these headquarters put into circulation 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report also details the gains that would be made from this international program by each country.
Indonesia, for example, would save $1 billion a year on electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants costing $2.5 billion to build.
