Vengeful hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks case has a double meaning.
On the one hand, an obvious scandal is revealed, a scandal that seems to be a scandal only in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it speaks of profound changes at the international level, and anticipates a future dominated by regression.
But let's proceed in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is a confirmation of the fact that every document compiled by the secret service (of any nation) consists entirely of press cuts.
The "extraordinary revelations" of Americans about Berlusconi's sex life are announced by what anyone could read in any newspaper for months (all except these two Berlusconi own), and the infamous cartoon profile of Gaddafi has long been a subject for cabaret artists to sketch.
The rule that secret documents may consist only of reports already known is crucial in the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
When you go to a bookstore that deals with esoteric literature, you will see that each work repeats (about the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Chateau, the Templars or the Masons) exactly what has already been written in previous works.
Not only because the author of occult texts does not like to search for new information (he does not even know where to look for reports about the non-existent), but because those who devote themselves to occultism believe only what they already know and what confirms what they have learned before.
That's Dan Brown's success mechanism.
The same goes for secret documents.
The informant is a lazy, and lazy (or limited spirit) head of the secret service (and if he is not, he could be, as I know, an editor in the Libération newspaper) who only takes for granted what he himself admits to be true.
The highly classified information about Berlusconi that the U.S. Embassy sent to the State Department was the same that Newsweek had published a week earlier.
Why, then, was there so much fuss about the disclosure of these documents?
On the one hand, they say what every cultured person already knows, namely that embassies, at least since the end of World War II and since the time when heads of state can make phone calls or fly away to dinner together, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small exercises in representation, have transformed themselves into spy centers.
Any viewer watching films about the investigation knows very well that it is only out of hypocrisy that it is seemingly ignored.
However, the fact that it is repeated in public dishonors the duty of hypocrisy and casts a bad light on American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can obtain the most highly classified information of the most powerful country in the world is a hard blow, not a negligible one, to the prestige of this state department.
The scandal affects both the victims and its "executors".
But let's get from here to the deep truth of what happened.
Once upon a time, in the time of Orwell, it was possible to conceive of all power, like some Big Brother who controlled every movement of his people.
Orvell’s prophecy has been proven ever since, thanks to the ability to control every move through the phone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway used, and so on, the citizen became a total victim of the wreath of power.
But when we demonstrate, as it is now, that even "graves" with the most secret information of the powerful can not resist the intervention of some hacker, the control message ceases to be one-way and becomes a circular.
Power is controlled by every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as the citizen's avenger - can know all the secrets of power.
How can he maintain a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets?
It is true that Georg Simmel has already said that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all information about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed a mysterious empty secret, because it is drawn from public life; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton’s secret was empty secrets.
WikiLeaks made no mistake about Sarkozy or Merkel, but it did something big for Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this blow to the bequeathed power?
It is clear that in the future states will not be able to send sensitive information online - this would be tantamount to its publication on a poster posted on a street corner.
But it’s also perfectly obvious that with current technology, it’s pointless to hope that you can keep a message secret over the phone.
There is nothing easier than to find out if and when the head of state traveled by plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and sensitive messages be kept secret in the future?
I know my prognosis is science fiction for the moment, and it is fantastic, but I must imagine government officials carrying discreetly the completion of formalities along uncontrollable routes and carrying only those messages that they know by heart or rather hide precious information in the heel of their shoes.
The information will be preserved in unique copies in key-closed drawers: all in all, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that the technology is now moving sideways forward, that is, backwards.
One century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet rehabilitated the wire-based (telephone) telegraph.
Videotapes (analogs) allowed cinema lovers to shoot the film step by step, moving it forward and backward and revealing all the secrets of the montage, while now CDs (numerical) allow only to jump through chapters, that is, macroporces.
By high-speed trains we arrive from Rome to Milan in three hours, while to travel by plane and transport, which includes we need three and a half hours.
It is therefore not uncommon for politics and communication techniques to revert to horse-drawn carriages.
One last note.
At other times, the press tried to understand what had been arranged in secret by the embassy.
Now it is the embassies that are asking for confidential information from the press.
Climate: How France Hacked Its Finance Promises
A year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to test compliance with promises for fast-unblocked funding (fast-start or early-start) implemented by developed countries.
And the big French hacks have been revealed
In the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion in 2010-2012.
The European Union has pledged 7.2 billion euros for three years, and France has pledged 1.26 billion euros (or 420 million euros per year).
At the launch of COP16, the EU pulled out a big ace to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: a report detailing the action of its member states, a press conference, a grand side event, the distribution of brochures...
A transparent operation priceless and valued for its real value: developed countries and civil society would like all developed countries and civil society to do it in the same way and with the same degree of accuracy.
The EU announced that it had mobilised EUR 2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to deliver on its promise of EUR 7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we focus on the detail, we find that things are much more complicated.
Under the Copenhagen Accord, these funds are "new and additional" to ensure that the increased burden is implemented without harming Public Development Assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission has proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 to be the reference year: international funding has been maintained and it is adding 150 million for three years of fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references with annual payment deadlines or with deadlines at the level of public development aid.
On the other hand, France considers the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous periods or to the global level of public aid for the development of d'Aide publique au développement.
Specifically, the total amount of France's support to developing countries may remain unchanged (or even decrease) to meet its commitment to financing "new and additional"...
Another crucial element is the division into gifts and loans.
There is not yet a rule and everyone chooses their own method of calculation.
Some people, such as France, think that 1 euro borrowed is equal to 1 euro donated.
Clearly, this is hard to prove: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be substantiated for some investments that are profitable (often emissions reduction projects involving more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present one euro that we receive as the equivalent of one euro that we give... , we should not understand it as the price of a loan to a creditor country (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France can only give such a justification: it is "keeping" its commitment of 420 million euros, 91.5% of which is a loan (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros) - see the EU document to verify this for yourself.
It is the only country in the European Union that uses a loan of this scale.
Germany demanded 46% from here, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) adhere to their obligations with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union gives 1 euro to satisfy its promise, France gives only 10 centimes and considers this effort comparable.
A beautiful juggler's piece!
To sum up, in its financing of the "fast start" France operates with a double sham: on the one hand with the development of the stock over time and on the other with the real financial burden.
Despite spending only 36.1 million euros, he is able to convince that he is spending 420 million euros "new and additional" in connection with his promises.
The manipulation of the Minister of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has made such decisions) could have a double negative impact, at the same time within the EU (why would Member States continue to donate when it is enough to lend?) and in the negotiations, because developing countries are not completely naive...
The chapter on early funding is just a small question, relatively short-term, in relation to a series of climate discussions.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in a huge machine like the UNFCCC.
Let's hope this isn't our case.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First of all, France should announce a change in its way of keeping accounts for 2011 and 2012, in the spirit of compliance with its obligations and fairness and fairness towards other countries of the European Union.
But most of all, France should avoid discussing long-term financing contributions (another crucial chapter currently under discussion): we will not escape the question of "additionality" or how to post loans.
France should change its stance to become as progressive on these deposits as it is on others.
So everyone is putting their hope in the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who is coming to Cancun next week.
The startling announcement of France's fast start and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans could trigger an increase in the level of international confidence necessary to advance the discussions.
Pesticide alarm for children.
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals one day, according to one study published this Wednesday, from the Association of Future Generations (ex-Rights Movement and Preservation of Future Generations).
The association, which points out that its results "do not have a significant statistical value given the low number of samples analyzed, but are characteristic of the issue being processed", bought between July and September foods commonly eaten in four meals and one light meal as a light snack for one child of roughly ten years old in supermarkets in l'Oise and Paris.
These typical dishes, including official recommendations - five pieces of fresh fruit and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day - as well as confectionery, were analyzed by research laboratories on chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The plate’s balance is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, 42 of which are carcinogenic, possible or likely, and five are clear carcinogens, as well as 37 substances that could act as endocrine disruptors (PEs), according to studies by several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
“Although in almost all cases the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, we see well in our research that the reality in consumer exposure to contaminants, possibly carcinogenic, and/or PE, is striking,” the association states.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea themselves contain about ten résiduums with possible carcinogenic effects and three proven as certain carcinogens, as is the case with about twenty residues that could disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil as a small snack, contains traces of six chemicals, including a banned fungicide in France.
The same applies to green beans from Kenya, included in the luncheon, where studies have found traces of strong insecticides banned in the EU.
In addition, minced meat steak, canned tuna and even bun and chewing gum were riddled with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
Salmon steak for dinner was the "richest" with 34 chemical residues discovered, and even the analysis of the plastic plate used to heat the food in the microwave oven did not escape analysis.
The ultimate risk to consumers of this "contaminant cocktail" is likely to be underestimated," the study concludes.
The Ecological Europe-Greening Association (EE-LV) has proposed a "face-to-face emergency" to set up a moratorium on the use of pesticides to halt "the rise of civilization diseases".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) examined the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, 76 of them in cereals.
